<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181869" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole ecuadorana Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole ecuadorana Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="413" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ecuadorana">Pheidole ecuadorana</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Etymology Named after the country of the type locality.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Diagnosis A medium-sized bicolorous (major) or light brown (minor) species with extremely long pilosity in both castes; narrow occiput with following collar in the minor; high, subangular humerus in dorsal-oblique view in the major; and mostly smooth shiny head and pronotum in both castes. The propodeal spiracle of the minor is unusual in its elliptical shape and position on the propodeum.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">
Most similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181870" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole erratilis Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole erratilis Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="413" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erratilis">erratilis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181873" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="413" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">flavifrons</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181922" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole petersoni Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole petersoni Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="413" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petersoni">petersoni</taxonomicName>
, but differing in many details of body shape, sculpturing, pilosity, as illustrated, and in color.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.82, HL 0.82, SL 0.50, EL 0.10, PW 0.42. Paratype minor: HW 0.50, HL 0.54, SL 0.50, EL 0.06, PW 0.32.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="413">color Major: head yellow with large, circular, medium-brown spot on vertex as shown; appendages yellow; rest of body brownish yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Minor: concolorous light brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Range Known only from the type series.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="413">Biology Collected in a clearing created by a tree fall in second-growth forest.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
